<tr>
	<td width="1%">&nbsp;</td>
	<td width="98%">
  
		<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">
		<tr>
		    <td valign="top">
		     <p><font face="Verdana" size="3"><b>Article Title:</b>&nbsp;</font>
		     <font face="Verdana" size="2">Wednesday News posts from Abashi</font><br>
		     <a href = "../Subscribe.asp?DID=213409" ><font face="Verdana" size="2">[Subscribe to this document]</font></a></p>
			 </td>
		</tr>
		
		<tr><td>&nbsp;</tr><tr>
		
		    <td valign="top"><div style= "padding:4;float: right"> <script language=JavaScript src=http://www.obsidian-tech.com/absolutebm/abmx.aspx?z=26></script></div><p><font face="Verdana" size="2">
		    <Blockquote>

<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/009100.html">Abashi, will it possible to customize SpellBook Look</a></B><P>

Spell Slot locations. It seems there are 3 different types of pages with diferent locations for empty slots, and that is VERY disturbing. I am kind of person who likes to see all thing IN SAME ORDER, so after getting my last rank spell I went crazy trying to make it LOOK NICE.<P>

<B>There are many new enhancements to the user interface planned. What ones will make the "final" product is too hard to say at the moment. Rowyl is doing the interface enhancements and he visits this board regularly and maintains a list of desired changes.<P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/009720.html">/new command please /consent all</a></B><P>

Basically yo give everyone consent to drag your corpse. Great for large hunts where lots of ppl may be dragging or relaying corpses. Fits in with a realistic view since anyone can pick up a corpse and drag it to safety.
Would be of great benefit imo.<BR>
/consent group<BR>
/consent guild<P>

<B>Giving *everyone* consent to drag your corpse would have too large of an abuse potential for us to consider entering it. Due to this abuse potential, we prefer that be expressly granted on a per-character basis.<P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/011021.html">Gordon- A reasonable question on experience and mana</a></B><P>

I was just wondering, why aren't these two things (mana and experience) delt with in numbers? Now I'm not saying "Bah! You need to tell us why wah wah wah nerf it blah blah" I'm just wondering why this is. In every other roleplay game I have played, this hasn't been much of an issue, it's just been there.<P>

<B>There are certain things that we do not want players to be able to calculate out to a "certainty". Experience and mana are things that we'd prefer remain mysterious in nature.<P>

I understand that values are given in pen and paper games, but I'd propose that they are only given because it *has* to be given, since there is no backend invisible process to make the calculations. Someone has to know what to do with the dice rolls.<P>

As for other CRPGs, people do not typically play them with the intention of min-maxing their way up to the most efficient combination of stats, gear, and skills possible, so it's not usually an issue there.<P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/011158.html">This is why I LIKE Verant!</a></B><P>

I am so glad that Brad and Gordon have tried to keep things on close and personal between the user base and themselves. This is VERY rare.<P>

Verant COULD very well release any and all information through their marketing department and/or PR agency instead of taking time to chat with people on the boards or in game.<P>

<B>Indeed. It's actually been recommended that we close the boards and go to a "Public answering of email" format used by a lot of companies out there, as then we'd only have to post what we'd like. <P>

Our current format provides a much closer and personal communications platform, which is what we want to support. Our goal is to have more *communication* with our customers as a whole than any other company out there. <P>

Thank you all for the positive comments :)<P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/011170.html">Diety Spawn Times. Can they be randomized?</a></B><P>

Diety Spawn Times. Can they be randomized? <P>

<B>Aside from initial spawns that occur once the servers come back up, anything with a spawn time of over two hours receives a random modifier to the spawn time that could cause it to spawn sooner or later than when expected. The modifier is percentage-based, so that the average spawn time (based on large numbers) is roughly the same as when they were spawning after an exact interval.<P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/011177.html">I pity the fools.</a></B><P>

Even if you can crush me, I'm having some kick ass fun with my ranger.<P>

<B>It's nice to hear someone get as passionate about having fun as others with negative issues :)<P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/011180.html">Tracking should be renamed Spawn Check</a></B><P>

Tracking is a wasted skill.. With all the spoiler sites everything is pretty much mapped out.. All most people use Tracking for is to see if that named mob that drops the "ph4t l3wtz" has spawned.<P>

<B>Perhaps for static spawns, however it's very useful for the rarer outdoor encounters. We also have some plans to enhance tracking for rangers in the near future.<P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/011185.html">Abashi's Reponses to Posts on this board about VEESHAN's PEAK...</a></B><P>

I think the main problem is.. there should be NO CONTEST as to whether or not you use any Veeshan's Peak loot. There are a great many robes that are *easy* to get and *much* better than that robe. And it's not one robe. I can think of two off the top of my head and I've never been to Veeshan's Peak.(The second one sucks for a different reason, but sucks none the less.)<P>

<B>That's certainly a valid opinion, but not how we decided to implement it in this case. From a game perspective, making every piece of loot in one zone obsolete everything in every other zone wouldn't make much sense. <P>

VP has it's extraordinary loot. In fact, most of it is extraordinary. That said, there are still some white elephants running around.<P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/011190.html">Running across norrath on 10 plat a day...</a></B><P>

There is no rational explanation that Abashi or Verant can give for having this long run.<P>

<B>Everfrost is a remote area, as intended. The long run back home is one of the ways that you pay for your exceptional stats and relatively good faction. </B><P>

If Verant wanted to really show that it valued it's customers time, it would increase the running speed of everything in norrath. This wouldn't affect game play, becuase teh MOBs would run faster too, simply change whatever variable that walking speed is set at, and double that. Suddenly, everybody in this game would be happy.<P>

<B>Somehow I doubt that anything so easy would "suddenly" make everyone happy :)<P>

Anyway, the size of the world is one of the aspects of gameplay, and that would certainly be affected by an across-the-board increase in running speed. Not to mention, the value of teleportation is based primarily upon its ability to reduce travel time.<P>

While I appreciate your suggestion, base running speed is a core foundation of EverQuest and not at all likely to be changed.</B><P>

Seriously though, they'll probably spout some nonsense about it shrinking the world or something.<P>

<B>I guess you win.<P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/011192.html">I tank, therefore...wait...I'm a wizard?</a></B><P>

Hehe, had some fun today.<P>

I'm probably the only wizard on the Cazic-Thule that actually has an FBSS for his waist slot (that's right. A few days ago, friends of mine and I did a Fire Giant raid. One of the Monks was complaining because I wouldn't lend him my FBSS. Mwahahahaa!)<P>

Anyways, a shaman friend of mine cast Alacrity or whatever on me. I was bored, figured, what the hey? We went out to North Karana, found me a hill giant, and melee'd it with my Dragoon Dirk. You heard me right. I went through about 50 some odd jaspers recasting steel skin, but I actually solo'd a Hill giant without nuking once. Hehe.<P>

I own. =p<P>

Sure, may not be what Verant had in mind when they said, "go out and have fun for once," but still...I think I'm gonna go try to solo a LDC next. Heheh.<P>

<B>ROFL :) Thanks for the story.<P>

I remember once in beta when I was checking out diamond skin. My wizard blew away one of the ice giants outside Permafrost before he got through the skin. This was of course before interrupts transferred through skins.<P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/011195.html">5 Boogeymen/30 clerics & revs.....</a></B><P>

OK Im pretty disturbed about this, the last 3 times fear was cleared there were on the average 5 boogeys 4, 6, 5 respectivly. Two out of three times nothing droped.(a blighted cap droped the 3rd time).
How is this fair when in hate there are so many clerics/revs/ninja mummys its crazy. When you made the change to the fingers you did something to the boogey spawn there used to be 8-10.<P>

<B>Additional fright fingers came from phoboplasm encounter tables, it didn't affect the number of boogey men.<P>

Anyway, the number of creatures of each type that can spawn is based upon percentages. Like anything else that involves random numbers, you can get good or bad rolls. Perhaps you end up with more targets and less loot, fewer targets and more loot, or unfortunately, even fewer targets with less loot. Three plane-clears do not represent enough trials to establish a meaningful average.<P>

Given that different servers have reported loot deficiencies for different classes, everything appears to be working properly.<P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/011199.html">Unprovoked (?) guard attack!</a></B><P>

1. Why did the harmless act of casting an Evo DD spell on another PC, outside of a duel, cause the guard to aggro?<P>

<B>The guards only care about the intent, not the affect. The guard only considers the spell, not whether that spell successfully landed. </B><P>

2. Why did the guard wait until the second cast to respond?<P>

<B>Guards roll to decide whether or not they are going to assist, based upon the faction of who is being attacked. </B><P>

Then she suggested I cast on her instead. No damage done, but I can still learn.<P>

<B>There you have the reason behind the answer for #1. Were there no negative impact to casting upon her, you could essentially macro up your skills in the safety of a city.<P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/011200.html">New /Who Feature?</a></B><P>

Would it be possible to implement a /who zone all feature?<P>

<B>The command does exist but is restricted to use by GMs and Guides. <P>

Due to the way player lists are compiled by the servers, opening this command for public use would place a load on our system infrastructure (processing time, network traffic, and outside bandwidth) beyond that which is appropriate given the benefit that the command would bestow. <P>

We have to keep a very close eye on the resources that are consumed by any feature in the game in order to maintain a playable environment for everyone.<P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/011203.html">A job well done!</a></B><P>

Looking through the messages it seems that most of them are complaints. <P>

<B>It's just easier to get people passionate about something that they don't like than something they do :)</B><P>

My only gripe would be some of the other players (which is funny because I play to meet other players hehe).<P>

<B>That's indeed one of the double-edged swords of online gaming. People play the games because it's fun to interact with other people, yet, it's also one of the bigger causes of frustration.</B><P>

I believe Everquest is what you make of it. That is the enjoyment of the experience. I hope (and plan) to spend many an enjoyable hour exploring Norrath in the years to come.<P>

<B>I'm glad to hear it. Thank you very much for your positive comments.<P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/011210.html">Credit where credit is due...</a></B><P>

Kudos to VI for dealing with the QA issue in a businesslike and professional fashion. Here's to success in bringing your QA processes into line.<P>

<B>*nods*<P>

Much thanks. We're constantly working to improve our processes for the betterment of the service.<P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/011227.html">Abashi: Do you get less xp for reds then blues?</a></B><P>

Now I am level 30. I was fighting blue Mountain Giants in Frontier Mountains most (blue to me at 30) for a while in a group of four all around 30 and getting great xp! Like noticable movement. Then I joined a group in Overthere fighting RED and YELLOW mobs with a group of four all around 30. We fought those mobs for a much greater time and ended up with much less experience.<P>

<B>Things can be a little harder to measure in level 30, which requires more experience than normal were the experience curve linear in nature. I would imagine that your experience might also have something to do with what will typically be more downtime between fights when encountering yellow and red NPCs.<P>

Also, while I can't say if the zones mentioned apply, some zones have greater or lesser experience modifiers than others. For instance, fighting in dungeons gives more experience per kill than fighting in most outdoor areas. The zone that gives the greatest experience modifier is actually on Faydwer, not Kunark.<P>

It is possible that a red in one zone could give less experience than a blue in another.<P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/011242.html">Burynai Legion Gi - possible race mistake</a></B><P>

Gnome Clerics can't wear the Burynai Legion Gi. Was this on purpose or did the programmer who put the races on it forget Gnomes could be Clerics and wear robes?<P>

<B>I'll look into it, however I've noticed that halflings aren't listed either, suggesting that it wasn't intended for small races.<P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/011243.html">A different kind of question for Gordon</a></B><P>

Hey Gordon: I'm going to be in San Diego on business in October. Does Verant give tours of its facilities to the public? If not, is there an opportunity for folks to drop by and say hello? I haven't seen this question addressed here or in the FAQ....<P>

<B>Due to the amount of development going on and the desire for secrecy, we do not give tours of the facility. We do however have events in various parts of the country to give players the opportunity to meet some of the people behind EverQuest.<P>

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/011248.html">Level limits on GM events? Why couldnt you do this with nagafen?</a></B><P>

I haven't seen the post that quote came from (though it sounds interesting) but when Abashi was commenting on the ability to prevent those over a certain level from hitting a mob, he mentioned that is was for GM controlled mobs.<P>

<B>Indeed. The ability to restrict by level is based upon the target being a "acted" NPC, rather an a computer-controlled NPC. I imagine that with enough work we could have implemented this for certain encounters, however we also wanted to restrict the level of assistance that could be offered on Nagafen/Vox raids by people level 53+. Under the original poster's suggestion, clerics for instance would still be able to offer 100% of their normal support to the raid regardless of level.<P>

-Gordon</B>
</blockquote>
